<HelpLayout title="Adding Plants" category="Plant Care" description="How to add plants, set care thresholds, and personalize your garden.">
  <p>
    Each plant in Plantgotchi gets its own profile with custom care thresholds. Here's how to
    set one up.
  </p>

  <h2>Creating a Plant Profile</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Open your <a href="/garden">Garden dashboard</a> and tap the "Add Plant" button.</li>
    <li>Give your plant a <strong>name</strong> — get creative! "Fernando the Fern" works great.</li>
    <li>Optionally set a <strong>species</strong> (e.g., "Monstera Deliciosa") for more targeted AI recommendations.</li>
    <li>Pick an <strong>emoji avatar</strong> from the selector — this appears on your plant card.</li>
    <li>Optionally add a <strong>photo URL</strong> if you want a real picture of your plant.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Setting Thresholds</h2>
  <p>
    Thresholds tell Plantgotchi when to alert you. You can customize these for each plant:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Metric</th><th>Default Min</th><th>Default Max</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Moisture</td><td>30%</td><td>80%</td><td>Good for most houseplants</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Temperature</td><td>15°C</td><td>30°C</td><td>Tropical plants may need higher</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    You can also set a <strong>light preference</strong> — low, medium, or high. This is used by the
    rule engine: if your plant prefers high light but the sensor reads below 1,000 lux, you'll get
    a gentle reminder to move it.
  </p>

  <h2>Light Preference Guide</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Low</strong> — under 1,000 lux (e.g., snake plant, pothos, ZZ plant)</li>
    <li><strong>Medium</strong> — 1,000–2,000 lux (e.g., philodendron, peace lily)</li>
    <li><strong>High</strong> — over 2,000 lux (e.g., succulents, herbs, fiddle leaf fig)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Editing and Deleting Plants</h2>
  <p>
    Tap on any plant card to open its detail view, then use the edit button to change its name,
    thresholds, or emoji. You can also delete a plant — this removes the plant profile but
    preserves historical sensor readings in the database.
  </p>
</HelpLayout>
